The Path to Nuclear Disarmament
NEW YORK – Massive weapons of destruction and disarmament present one of the most challenging tasks the world currently faces. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that transcend borders.
A world without nuclear weapons is a paramount general good.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My homeland South Korea has suffered from the devastation of conventional wars and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
However, such threat scenarios exist naturally not only in Asia.
Although the use of nuclear weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an aspiration.
Is a taboo that applies only to the use of such weapons really sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
Still, the UN plays a crucial role in this.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and educate to achieve our agreed goals and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to renounce nuclear weapons and have summarized their obligations under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which explains the estimated 26,000 existing weapons.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of atomic deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and introducing new risks of nuclear weapons being used.
The world is still concerned about the nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we may be facing a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is viewed as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that needs to be protected against proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
Yet the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let us consider the immense opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Stockholm International Institute for Peace Research), military expenditures rose last year to over $1.3 trillion.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total costs of nuclear weapons alone in the United States at over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
This is, by any definition, a huge investment that could have been directed towards many other productive goals.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers they pose have sparked a global debate, breathing new life into the cause of nuclear disarmament.
We experienced the UN Disarmament Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven-Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan founded the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Citizen groups and states with nuclear weapons have also put forward proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own five-point plan.
Firstly: I call on all parties to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to fulfill their obligations under the treaty and to engage in negotiations for effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they could negotiate an arms control convention supported by a strong verification system, as has been proposed for a long time in the UN.
I have circulated a draft for such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this topic together with other states at the UN Disarmament Conference in Geneva, the only multilateral disarmament negotiation forum in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the USA and Russia, aimed at significantly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The proposal by the United Kingdom to hold a conference of the nuclear powers on the topic of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly make it known to the states that do not possess nuclear weapons that they will not become victims of a nuclear weapon attack or its threat.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Weapons Ban Treaty should cease their nuclear weapons programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoria on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials may only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Nuclear Test Ban Treaty into force, as well as impetus for the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without preconditions take up talks on a convention regarding fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
Moreover, I urge all parties to the Nuclear Weapons Ban Treaty to conclude security arrangements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily adopt the stricter safety clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they are doing to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no authoritative estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the necessity for greater transparency.
And finally, various additional measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of massive weapons of destruction, new efforts against terrorism involving massive weapons, limitations on the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new weapon bans, including those for rockets and space weapons.
If real, verified progress in disarmament is made, the ability to eliminate the atomic threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we make it harder to carry out terrorist attacks with weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a fresh start not only for disarmament but also for strengthening our system of international peace and security.
